## R Markdown | Using Markdown to create documents.

## Session 1 - Markdown Basics. 
- The YAML header.  
`---`   \
`title: "A presentation using ioslides"`.  \
`subtitle: "Reproducible Research in R"
`.  \
`author: "Mark Fernandes".`.  \
`date: "2025-03-07"`   \
`--- ` \

- Headings (with different levels).  \
 Bold (2* or 2_). \
 Italics (1* or 1_). \
 Superscript (2'^') Subscript (2'~'). \ 
 Inline code (back-tick)  Strike-through text (2~) \ 
 Line breaks (2 spaces or use `\` & newline).  

## Beautiful equations!
LaTEX equation syntax can be inserted and rendered by MarkDown.  
`
$$f(k) = {n \choose k} p^{k} (1-p)^{n-k}$$`
$$f(k) = {n \choose k} p^{k} (1-p)^{n-k}$$
\

We can also use HTML tags like `<U>` for underlining:    
<U>Underlined text</U> \
and other HTML tricks like: \
<marquee>This moves!</marquee>

## Link navigation

- Within document between anchors:  
`# Markdown {#markdown-header}` \

then to navigate use :  
`[link to header](#markdown-header)`.  \

- Link to a web-page   
`[text of link](https://training.cam.ac.uk/bioinformatics/event-timetable)` \

- Insert an image via a URL or path
`![Figure caption](path to image)`
![Rlogo on web page](data:image/png;base64,)

## Lists
### Ordered lists

`1. item 1` \

`2. item 2. ` \

1. item 1. 
2. item 2. 

## Lists
### Unordered lists
- In an unordered bulletted list, each item begins with *, + or -. If indented by 4 spaces point moves to a new sub-heading.   

* Item 2.  \
* Item 3.  \
    * Item 3a. \  
        * Item 3a(i).  \
    * Item 3b. \

## Task lists
`- [ ] an unchecked task list item ` \
`- [x] checked item` \


- [ ] an unchecked task list item. 
- [x] checked item.

`| Column 1    | Column 2    |` \
`| ----------- | ----------- |` \
